<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="341" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1605,1975]" pageId="9" pageNumber="341">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,320,1883,1906]" pageId="9" pageNumber="341">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet of the new species, 
<taxonomicName box="[809,871,1883,1906]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Hyadaphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphidomorpha" pageId="9" pageNumber="341" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis box="[809,871,1883,1906]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="341">parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Latin adjective, in nominative feminine (as 
<taxonomicName authority="Remaudière, 1959" authorityName="Remaudière" authorityYear="1959" box="[151,253,1917,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="Hydaphis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="341" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,253,1917,1941]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="341">Hydaphis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and singular, which means small, in reference to the short body length of this aphid. This name already was handwritten on the slide labels by D. Hille Ris Lambers, who never formally described the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
